Script pitch to @jcooney7, written by ChatGPT and to star moi and @beneluxflux: 

In "Acid Pursuit," Officer Rick Davis and Jake "Sunshine" Thompson, accompanied by their mischievous dog Groovy, accidentally find themselves embroiled in a mind-altering acid trip while being chased by the mafia. Amidst the ensuing chaos, they embark on a journey of self-discovery and learn unexpected life lessons.

Rick, a strict and by-the-book police officer, is investigating a mafia case, while Jake, a peace-loving hippy, is peacefully protesting against the establishment. Their paths cross when Rick mistakenly identifies Jake's protest as a potential riot. In the resulting confusion, a vial of potent acid is spilled, inadvertently dosing Rick, Jake, and Groovy.

As the acid takes hold, their perceptions and reality become warped, leading to a series of comedic misadventures. Along the way, they encounter a colorful cast of eccentric characters—a talking tree, a wisecracking street performer—who impart valuable lessons on acceptance, open-mindedness, and embracing spontaneity.

While evading the pursuing mafia, who seek the vial of acid they unknowingly possess, Rick and Jake form an unlikely bond. Rick learns to let go of his rigidity, embracing life's unpredictability, while Jake discovers the importance of responsibility and finding a balance between freedom and accountability.

Throughout their journey, Groovy the dog serves as the catalyst for their transformation, bringing joy and laughter in even the most chaotic situations.

Ultimately, Rick and Jake outsmart the mafia by relying on their newfound camaraderie, unconventional thinking, and the lessons they've absorbed. They emerge from their acid-induced escapade with a deeper understanding of themselves and the world.

"Acid Pursuit" is a comedy replete with zany situations, vibrant characters, and unexpected insights. It reminds us that profound discoveries can arise from the most unconventional circumstances.

I have many favorite films that appeal to aspects of my heart at different times of my life. "Synecdoche, New York" for my midlife crisis (aka reassessment) and "Moulin Rouge" for the simple message of "Nature Boy" (written by eden ahbe) presented in glorious Absinth paisley decadence. Finally got to see the stage show on the West End. While I enjoyed it and cried from the sheer emotion the music evokes, it did feel stretched and tethered tighter to the ground. Some of the additional music/mashups are great ("Crazy" 🥰) while others felt a tad pandering. And the producers undercut the message of "Nature Boy" in lieu of making the audience forget they saw a tragedy. Lol! Still definitely worth seeing!

We're delighted to today reveal our first GUEST OF HONOUR for London Anime & Gaming Con this 16-18th February 2023 (tickets available now @ www.londonanimecon.com) - D.C. Douglas!

After 30 years in “The Biz," it's easiest to just get to the beef: 

VIDEO GAMES: Rayvis in the new “Star Wars Jedi: Survivor,” Svarog in “Honkai: Star Rail,” Albert Wesker in 9 "Resident Evil" games from 2007's "Umbrella Chronicles" to 2019's "Teppen" - over a decade of badassery. Then there's Legion in "Mass Effect" 2 & 3, Kamoshida in "Persona 5," Pod 042 in "Nier: Automata" and Grimoire Noir in "Nier: Replicant,” G1 Michigan in “Armored Core VI,” Burton in "Borderlands 3," Azrael in "Blazeblue," Raven in "Tekken 6 & 8," foxy grandpa Gunter in "Fire Emblem: Fates," 89 in "AI: The Somnium Files,” Rufus and Valimar in the "Trails" series, and many more Japanese RPGs and indie American games. 

ANIME:  X Drake in "One Piece," Yoshikage Kira in "Jojo's Bizarre Adventure," Kalego in "Welcome To Demon School, Iruma-Kun," Shinji in "Lycoris Recoil," Geo in "Bastard!,” Ryu in "Shaman King 2021," The Praetorian in "Super Crooks," Master in "Akudama Drive," Randle in "Tiger & Bunny," Edo in Netflix's "Ultraman," Battuta in "How NOT to Summon a Demon lord," Gekko in "Boruto: Naruto Next Generations," Kershner in "Sirius The Jaeger," Igari in "Baki," Ryu in the cult hit "Backstreet Girls: Gokudolls," Kamoshida in "Persona 5: the Animation," Shoot McMahon in "Hunter x Hunter," Locus in "Berserk," The Professor in "Cyborg 009," Jasley in "Mobile Suit Gundam: IBO" season 2, Vincent Pike in "MSGT: Bandit Flower," Genji Kamogawa in "Hajime no ippo," and many more only 12 people know about. 

CARTOONS: Deathstroke in "DC Super Hero Girls," Newton on "The Rocketeer," Chase on "Transformers: Rescue Bots," Colonel Rawls on the final season of "Regular Show," Superman on "Family Guy," Mick in "The Tom and Jerry Show," and a few pilots that died lonely and unseen.

Happy New Years! I started my New Years resolution in June after seeing video of me singing "Sweet Transvestite" at a con kareoke. It started with more weight training, apple watch, protein, lots of vitamin D3/K2 and intermittent fasting. It's mushroomed since then into all sorts of health measuring and dietary changes and this week I added in VR cardio with @getsupernatural (arm and chest weights added today) on Meta Quest! It's NYE and I finished a crazy day of cardio with a hot tub. I'm still not at my goal... But when I get there.... Oh baby! Definitely redoing that "sweet transvestite" video!

I hope someone who sees this gets inspired to love themselves enough to take charge of their health. It'll be the start of their best relationship!

Much love to you all, strangers and friends alike! 🤗💕🕺🎆🎇
